The '''Hartsville Nuclear Plant''' is a canceled [[nuclear power plant]] project located near [[Hartsville, Tennessee]]. To be built and operated by the [[Tennessee Valley Authority]], it was to have four [[General Electric]] [[boiling water reactor]]s.
[[File:Hartsville-cooling-tower-tn1.jpg|thumb|A [[cooling tower]] from the canceled plant]]
Land along the [[Cumberland River]] was acquired by TVA in the late 1960s for construction of the plant which was to accommodate the electricity demand for the 1980s. Construction began in 1975. The Plant B reactors were canceled on March 22, 1983 and the Plant A reactors were canceled on August 29, 1984.<ref name="Hartsville_EA">{{cite web |title=Hartsville Nuclear Plant Site, Transfer of TVA Property For Industrial Park |url=http://www.tva.gov/environment/reports/hartsville/hartsville_ea.pdf |author=[[Tennessee Valley Authority]] |accessdate=August 28, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090105233433/http://www.tva.gov/environment/reports/hartsville/hartsville_ea.pdf |archivedate=January 5, 2009 |df= }}</ref>
There are currently plans to turn {{convert|550|acres}} of the {{convert|1940|acres|adj=on}} property into an [[industrial park]]<ref name="Hartsville_EA" /> similar to what became of the [[WNP-3 and WNP-5|Satsop Nuclear Plant]] in [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]].
